flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn decision truth into action and outcome truth"]
    G2["Keep this path narrower than decision formation and narrower than append-only audit truth"]
    G3["Answer how a decision begins affecting the rest of the system in a deterministic, duplicate-safe, and attributable way"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The entry is not raw traffic and not generic RTDL health"]
    E2["The entry is decision truth that has already been formed under the current run scope"]
    E3["RTDL catch-up closure is already green before the decision chain is allowed to proceed"]
    E4["The run-process then requires the decision lane, the action and outcome evidence, and the append-only audit evidence as distinct closure elements"]
    E5["This path begins after decision formation, not before it"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["Decision truth"]
    R2["Action layer"]
    R3["Committed and/or published outcome surfaces"]
    R4["Downstream RTDL and cross-plane consumers"]
    R5["Action and outcome boundary is owned rather than assumed"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["The decision itself"]
    C2["Run context"]
    C3["Policy and bundle context"]
    C4["The trace from decision to action"]
    C5["Concrete proof concerns at this boundary: action commit success rate, duplicate side-effect error rate, ambiguity and quarantine rate, action latency, and decision-to-action trace completeness"]
    C6["This boundary carries more than a bare allow/deny flag"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats side effects and outcomes as their own truth boundary, not as an invisible consequence of decisioning"]
    L2["The system is not saying once decision formation produced a decision, the world will somehow be affected"]
    L3["There is a dedicated layer that owns how decision truth becomes action and outcome truth under the platform's at-least-once and ambiguity rules"]
    L4["That is strong A-level design signal because it makes the hot path legible beyond mere scoring"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The copied baseline wired graphs show live action deployment alongside the context, entity, feature, guardrail, decision, audit, and archive surfaces in the RTDL namespace"]
    S2["So the action layer is concrete live workload in the current RTDL plane, not just a design box on the graph"]
    S3["The same baseline network shows the downstream handoff: the decision and action surfaces publish to the RTDL downstream topic"]
    S4["So the path is visible both as runtime workload and as a named downstream transport boundary"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform refuses to let decision correctness and side-effect correctness collapse into one fuzzy notion that the hot path worked"]
    Y2["The run-process separates the decision chain into decision lane, action and outcome evidence, and append-only audit evidence"]
    Y3["That means action and outcome truth is intentionally given its own owned closure"]
    Y4["The readiness definition sharpens why: duplicate safety, deterministic action commits, ambiguity recording, and trace completeness are first-class properties rather than operator cleanup after the fact"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The RTDL plane contract says actions and audit outputs must be correct, not just the decisions"]
    X2["The action-layer contract says side effects must be duplicate-safe, deterministic, attributable, and ambiguity-aware"]
    X3["The bus and topic contract says the decision and action surfaces are explicit producers of the RTDL downstream topic"]
    X4["So action and outcome emission participates in a named downstream handoff rather than an undefined local effect"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately adds another explicit boundary to the hot path"]
    T2["That costs complexity because the platform must preserve duplicate-safe semantics, ambiguity recording instead of burying it, and decision-to-action attribution"]
    T3["But that complexity buys stronger system-design property"]
    T4["Later case, label, audit, and replay paths can treat action and outcome truth as explicit and owned, rather than inferring it from side effects that probably happened"]
    T5["The docs are clear that the platform is not allowed to mix ambiguity with normal outcomes or depend on operator cleanup to make actions look deterministic"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still ingest traffic, form context, materialize features, classify guardrail posture, and even produce decision"]
    N2["But it loses a clean answer to what concrete outcome followed from that decision"]
    N3["It loses a clean answer to whether the outcome was committed safely under duplicates and retries"]
    N4["It loses a clean answer to whether that outcome can be traced back to the right decision, run, bundle, and policy"]
    N5["Without this path, the RTDL plane would have a decision boundary but no explicit owner for how decisions become platform effects"]
    N6["That would weaken A immediately"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["Deterministic action and outcome truth attributable to the right decision, run, bundle, and policy context"]
    O2["Action commits and/or publishes have happened in the platform's owned way"]
    O3["Ambiguity has been recorded rather than silently leaked"]
    O4["Owned outcome: explicit platform effects that are duplicate-safe, attributable, and ambiguity-aware"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for turning decisions into action and outcome truth"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>duplicate safety, ambiguity recording, and attribution are designed properties, not accidental behavior"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the action layer is a live named workload in the current RTDL plane, and action and outcome evidence is a required part of the decision-chain closure"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>this path is governed by duplicate-safe side-effect rules, decision-to-action trace completeness, and the decision-and-action to RTDL-topic contract"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>the platform already knows side effects are dangerous under at-least-once conditions, which is why the action layer is defined around duplicate safety and ambiguity discipline rather than convenience"]
    A6["A-level meaning:<br/>the RTDL plane has an explicit owner for how decisions become platform effects instead of leaving the consequences of decisioning implicit"]
  end

